The defendant Anton D Bratton was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Anton D Bratton in court with attorney Gabriela A Leija.  Student Intern Matt Adrian appearing with Margaret Anne Kunisch appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Statements made as to Sentencing by both counsel and Defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:    Defendant sentenced to serve 90 DAYS in the House of Correction (HOC) to run consecutive to cases 15CM003255 and 15CM003844 with credit for 10 days time served.  Huber privileges under Sec.303.08 Wis. Stats. to apply work and school.

Court IMPOSED AND STAYED the sentence and placed Defendant on Probation with the State of Wisconsin, Department of Corrections for a period of 24 MONTHS to run concurrent to cases 15CM003255 and 15CM003844 with the following conditions as to probation:
*  No new  law violations reaching the level of a probable cause finding.
*  Cooperate with agent.
*  Pay costs, surcharges, assessments, supervision, victim, and DNA fees to be paid prior to the end of the probationary period.  Failure to pay shall result in a Civil Judgment with tax intercept.
*  Maintain full time / part time employment and or schooling.
*  ABSOLUTE SOBRIETY.
*  AODA assessment with follow up care and treatment.
*  Random urine screens with no positive results.  No association with drug users, drug dealers, drug houses, or drug dealings.
*  Mental Health assessment and treatment.
*  Participate in any anger management courses and cooperate fully.
*  No contact with with Julius B. (Father); Yolanda S. (mother) will be at the discretion of the agent.
*  No contact with Enyinnay U.
*  Defendant required to provide a biological specimen (DNA) to the State Crime Lab for testing.

Defendant changes his plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.   Defendant advised that if not a United States Citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant guilty and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs.

State does not object to defense motion to modify bail.  Court modifies bail to $1,000.00 SIGNATURE BOND.
